com.esri.mo2.map.elt
Class BaseElement

java.lang.Object
  |
  +--com.esri.mo2.map.elt.BaseElement
All Implemented Interfaces:
Cloneable, Data, Element, Identifiable, MapData, Spatial
Direct Known Subclasses:
BaseElement, BaseGroupElement, FeatureElement, GraphicElement, ImageElement, LegendElement, MapElement, NorthArrowElement, OverviewMapElement, ScaleBarElement, TextElement
public abstract class BaseElement
extends Object
implements Element

The abstract class provides an essential implementation of the inferface com.esri.mo2.map.core.Element. Its subclass providing concrete implementation can be added into any element container, such as PageLayout.

setDataID

public void setDataID(DataID dataid)
Description copied from interface: Element
DataID is a unique identification for the element to be added to an element container/searchable object. It will be used as a key for storing/retrieving an Element object in an element container or searchable object. The contains such as BaseLayout and GraphicsLayer will assign a DataID to an Element when it is added. Developers must set the DataID if the element is going to be added into an element container or searchable object that doesn't generate a DataID for the element. The com.esri.mo2.map.mem.MemorySearchable class is a such container since an Element is also a com.esri.mo2.data.feat.Identifiable object that could be added MemorySearchable.

Specified by:
setDataID in interface Element
Parameters:
dataid - the DataID
See Also:
Element.setDataID(com.esri.mo2.data.feat.DataID)

invalidate

public void invalidate()
Description copied from interface: Element
Invalidates the Element's Geometry. Some Elements allow you to get a reference to the underlying geometry and modify it directly. If you choose to do this, you must also call invalidate() to ensure the geometry changes are noticed by the underlying memory Dataset. If you fail to do this, then strange effects may occur when you try to select modified data. Alternatively, if you use the Element's move() or translate() methods, you don't need to call invalidate() - this will automatically be done for you.

Specified by:
invalidate in interface Element
See Also:
Element.invalidate()
